# Production Deployment — {{ project.name }}

This generated deployment package is intentionally simple: Docker Compose on a VPS or container host. It is not a Kubernetes setup and it does not make the project production-ready by itself.

## Generated deployment files

```text
backend/Dockerfile
frontend/Dockerfile
deploy/docker-compose.prod.yml
deploy/.env.example
docs/deployment.md
```

## 1. Prepare environment

Copy the example environment file and replace every placeholder value:

```bash
cp deploy/.env.example deploy/.env
```

Required values include:

- `DATABASE_URL`
- `REDIS_URL`
- `SECRET_KEY`
- `BACKEND_BASE_URL`
- `BACKEND_SERVICE_TOKEN`
{% for bot in bots %}
- `{{ bot.token_env }}`
- `{{ bot.key | upper }}_WEBHOOK_URL`
- `{{ bot.key | upper }}_WEBHOOK_SECRET`
{% endfor %}
- `VITE_API_BASE_URL`
{% if has_celery_worker %}
- `CELERY_BROKER_URL`
- `CELERY_RESULT_BACKEND`
{% endif %}

Do not commit `deploy/.env`.

## 2. Build images

From the generated project root:

```bash
docker compose -f deploy/docker-compose.prod.yml --env-file deploy/.env build
```

The frontend image uses `VITE_API_BASE_URL` at build time. Set it to the public backend URL that browser clients should call.

## 3. Start services

```bash
docker compose -f deploy/docker-compose.prod.yml --env-file deploy/.env up -d
```

Services:

- `backend`: FastAPI served by Uvicorn on port `${BACKEND_PORT:-8000}`
- `frontend`: Vite static build served by nginx on port `${FRONTEND_PORT:-8080}`
- `postgres`: PostgreSQL 16
- `redis`: Redis 7
{% if has_celery_worker %}
- `celery_worker`: Celery worker using the generated backend image
{% endif %}

## 4. Database migration

Generated projects include an Alembic scaffold wired to the generated SQLAlchemy models. The generator does not create a fake initial migration. Before production use, create and verify the initial migration from the generated models:

```bash
cd backend
alembic revision --autogenerate -m "initial"
alembic upgrade head
```

Run these commands against a disposable database first and review the generated revision before applying it to production.

## 5. Health checks

Backend:

```bash
curl http://localhost:${BACKEND_PORT:-8000}/health
```

Frontend:

```bash
curl http://localhost:${FRONTEND_PORT:-8080}/
```

## 6. Bale webhook registration

After the backend is reachable over HTTPS, register each bot webhook using the generated Bale client factory.

{% for bot in bots %}
`{{ bot.title }}` (`{{ bot.key }}`):

```python
from bale.shared.client import make_{{ bot.key }}_client

client = make_{{ bot.key }}_client()
await client.set_webhook("https://your-domain.example{{ bot.webhook_path }}", secret_token="...")
